\nIf `eventToAction` can return undefined (for events that don't map to actions), then the first form works. If it always returns an Action, the second form works.\n\nHmm, thinking about it more — `eventToAction` probably handles ALL AgentEvents, including `usage`, `aborted`, `error`. These likely DO have corresponding Actions (usage updates token counts, error sets error state, etc.). So `eventToAction` probably always returns an Action. In that case, the second form works.\n\nBut wait — `assistant-start` might not have an Action if the reducer doesn't need it. But then eventToAction would need to return undefined for it, making the return type `Action | undefined`.\n\nArgh. I keep going back and forth.\n\nOK, let me just go with direct action dispatch. I'm confident about `tool-call` and `assistant-done`. For `assistant-start`, I'll include it. If it's not a valid Action, I'll... well, I can't fix it after submission. But I think it is valid.\n\nLet me also consider: what if I DON'T include `assistant-start` and the reducer creates a pending message on the first `tool-call`? Then `tool-call` + `assistant-done` works. If the reducer REQUIRES `assistant-start` first, then without it, the `tool-call` might be ignored (no pending message to attach to), and `assistant-done` creates an empty message. Then `toolSnapshot` would be empty. The test would fail.\n\nSo including `assistant-start` is safer IF it's a valid action. And if the reducer doesn't require it, including it is harmless (it just creates a pending message that the tool-calls attach to).\n\nThe only risk is if `assistant-start` is not a valid Action variant. Let me assess this risk. The AgentEvent `assistant-start` exists. `eventToAction` maps it to something. If it maps to an `assistant-start` Action, then it exists. If eventToAction drops it (returns undefined), then... but then the reducer would never create pending messages, which doesn't make sense. So `assistant-start` must be an Action.\n\nI'm confident. Including `assistant-start`.\n\nFINAL. Let me write all three files now.\n\nWait, one more thing about the test. For case 3 (Option A drop), the fixture has only a child assistant message (no parent). The child has `parent_tool_use_id: 'toolu_AGENT'`. The adapter emits the child tool-call. But there's no parent Agent tool-call. That's fine — the test only checks that no text-delta is emitted and the child tool-call IS emitted.\n\nBut wait — the `result` line has `stop_reason: 'end_turn'`. The adapter sets `stopReason = 'end_turn'`. Then `cliStopReason('end_turn', false)` = 'end'. So the last event is `assistant-done` with `stopReason: 'end'`. Good. And no `text-delta` events. Good.\n\nActually, let me double-check: the child assistant message has `parent_tool_use_id: 'toolu_AGENT'` (a string). `stringField(evt, 'parent_tool_use_id')` returns `'toolu_AGENT'`. So the child path runs: `emitChildToolCalls` emits the tool-call for `toolu_CHILD`, then `break`. No text-delta. \n\nLet me also verify: in `emitChildToolCalls`, the content array has a `text` block and a `tool_use` block. The function iterates and only emits for `tool_use` blocks (it checks `stringField(block, 'type') !== 'tool_use'` and continues). So the text block is skipped. No text-delta. \n\nOK, writing the files now. For real this time.\n\nLet me also make sure the `ToolCallEvent` type has `parentToolUseId` and `args`. From the brief: `{ type: 'tool-call'; id: string; toolCallId: string; name: string; args: unknown; parentToolUseId?: string }`. So `Extract<AgentEvent, { type: 'tool-call' }>` has `parentToolUseId?: string` and `args: unknown`. Good. `childCall!.parentToolUseId` is `string | undefined`. `childCall!.args` is `unknown`. `expect(parentCall.args).toEqual(...)` — `toEqual` accepts `unknown`. Good.\n\nFor `ToolStatusEvent`: `{ type: 'tool-status'; toolCallId: string; status: ...; ... }`. The `status` field — from `emitFromUserEcho`, it yields `{ type: 'tool-status', toolCallId, status: 'result', result: block.content }` or `{ type: 'tool-status', toolCallId, status: 'error', error: ... }`. So `status` is `'result' | 'error'`. `childStatus!.status` should be `'result'`. Good.\n\nWait, what's the exact `status` type? It might be `'pending' | 'running' | 'result' | 'error'` or similar. `'result'` should be valid. `expect(childStatus!.status).toBe('result')` — this compares the actual value. Good.\n\nAlright, let me write everything out now.\n\nOh wait, I also need to double-check: in the `user` case, I removed the `parent_tool_use_id` guard. So now BOTH parent and child `user` records go through `emitFromUserEcho`. For the child `user` record (with `parent_tool_use_id: 'toolu_AGENT'`), `emitFromUserEcho` extracts the `tool_result` block with `tool_use_id: 'toolu_CHILD'` and emits a `tool-status`. Good. For the parent `user` record (with `parent_tool_use_id: null`), it extracts the `tool_result` with `tool_use_id: 'toolu_AGENT'` and emits a `tool-status`. Good.\n\nSo in case 4, there should be TWO `tool-status` events: one for `toolu_CHILD` and one for `toolu_AGENT`. The test checks for the child one. Good.\n\nLet me also verify case 1: the events should include `assistant-start`, `tool-call` (Agent), `tool-call` (Bash, child), `tool-status` (CHILD result), `tool-status` (AGENT result), `usage`, `assistant-done`. The last event is `assistant-done` with `stopReason: 'end'`. Good.\n\nWait, is there a `usage` event? The `result` line has `usage: { input_tokens: 9, output_tokens: 4 }`. Since `sawStreamEvent` is false, `emitUsageFromResult` runs and emits a `usage` event. So yes, there's a `usage` event before `assistant-done`. But the LAST event is `assistant-done`. Good.\n\nOK, writing now.\n\nActually, I realize I should double-check one thing in the adapter. The `result` case:\n```ts\ncase 'result': {\n  sawResult = true;\n  const resultStop = stringField(evt, 'stop_reason');\n  if (resultStop !== undefined) {\n    stopReason = resultStop;\n  }\n  if (!sawStreamEvent) {\n    yield* emitUsageFromResult(evt);\n  }\n  break;\n}\n```\n\nThis sets `stopReason = 'end_turn'`. Then after the loop, `cliStopReason('end_turn', false)` = 'end'. Good.\n\nNow let me write the final files.\n\nFor the adapter, I need to be very careful to only change the three cases and add the helper. Let me copy the original and apply changes.\n\nLet me write it all out now.","reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":"Let me carefully implement the three files per the brief.\n\nFirst, `src/providers/claudeCliClient.ts` — I need to modify the three drop guards (a), (b), (c) and add the `emitChildToolCalls` helper. Everything else unchanged.\n\nSecond, `src/ui/Message.tsx` — restructure committed render to nest child tool cards under parent.\n\nThird, `tests/nestedSubagentRender.test.ts` — new test file.\n\nLet me write the adapter file. I'll take the current file and apply the exact changes specified.\n\nFor the `assistant` case:\n```ts\ncase 'assistant': {\n  const message = asObject(evt.message);\n  if (message === undefined) break;\n  const parentToolUseId = stringField(evt, 'parent_tool_use_id');\n  if (parentToolUseId !== undefined) {\n    yield* emitChildToolCalls(message, input, parentToolUseId);\n    break;\n  }\n  const stop = stringField(message, 'stop_reason');\n  if (stop !== undefined && stop !== null) stopReason = stop;\n  if (sawStreamEvent) break;\n  yield* emitFromContentBlocks(message, input, toolCalls);\n  break;\n}\n```\n\nWait, the original code checks `evt.parent_tool_use_id !== null && evt.parent_tool_use_id !== undefined`. The new design uses `stringField(evt, 'parent_tool_use_id')` which returns undefined if not a string. So if it's null, stringField returns undefined (since null is not a string), and we proceed as parent. Good — that matches the ground truth that parent has `null`.\n\nFor `stream_event` case — keep the guard, add comment.\n\nFor `user` case — remove the guard.\n\nNow the helper `emitChildToolCalls`.\n\nLet me write the full file.\n\nFor Message.tsx, I need to:\n- Build `childrenByParent: Map<parentId, Block[]>` from tool blocks whose `parentOf(toolCallId)` is defined.\n- Iterate blocks in order:\n  - text → render text\n  - tool that is a child → skip\n  - tool that is parent/standalone → render ToolCallCard, then render children as nested ToolCallCard\n- Fallback: child whose parent block not present → render at top level.\n\nLet me think about how to render. The `renderBlock` function currently handles a single block. I need to restructure the main render to handle the grouping.\n\nLet me rewrite the `Message` component.\n\n```tsx\nexport function Message({ msg, depth }: MessageProps): ReactElement {\n  const d = depth ?? DEPTH;\n\n  const parentOf = (toolCallId: string): string | undefined =>\n    msg.toolSnapshot?.[toolCallId]?.parentToolUseId;\n\n  // Build childrenByParent map (committed only).\n  const childrenByParent = new Map<string, Block[]>();\n  if (msg.toolSnapshot !== undefined) {\n    for (const block of msg.blocks) {\n      if (block.kind !== 'tool') continue;\n      const pid = parentOf(block.toolCallId);\n      if (pid === undefined) continue;\n      const arr = childrenByParent.get(pid);\n      if (arr === undefined) {\n        childrenByParent.set(pid, [block]);\n      } else {\n        arr.push(block);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Track child blocks that have been rendered under their parent.\n  const renderedChildren = new Set<string>();\n\n  const elements: ReactElement[] = [];\n  for (const block of msg.blocks) {\n    if (block.kind === 'text') {\n      elements.push(\n        <Text key={block.id} color={token(roleToken(msg.role), d)}>\n          {block.text}\n        </Text>\n      );\n      continue;\n    }\n    // tool block\n    const pid = parentOf(block.toolCallId);\n    if (pid !== undefined) {\n      // It's a child. If its parent block is also in this message, it renders\n      // under the parent (skip here). Otherwise render at top level (fallback).\n      const parentBlockPresent = msg.blocks.some(\n        (b) => b.kind === 'tool' && b.toolCallId === pid,\n      );\n      if (parentBlockPresent) {\n        continue; // rendered under parent\n      }\n      // fallback: render at top level (not nested, since parent not here)\n      const tool = msg.toolSnapshot?.[block.toolCallId];\n      elements.push(\n        tool !== undefined ? (\n          <ToolCallCard key={block.id} tool={tool} depth={d} />\n        ) : (\n          <Text key={block.id} color={token('textDim', d)}>\n            [tool {block.toolCallId}]\n          </Text>\n        ),\n      );\n      continue;\n    }\n    // parent or standalone tool block\n    const tool = msg.toolSnapshot?.[block.toolCallId];\n    elements.push(\n      tool !== undefined ? (\n        <ToolCallCard key={block.id} tool={tool} depth={d} />\n      ) : (\n        <Text key={block.id} color={token('textDim', d)}>\n          [tool {block.toolCallId}]\n        </Text>\n      ),\n    );\n    // render children\n    const children = childrenByParent.get(block.toolCallId);\n    if (children !== undefined) {\n      for (const childBlock of children) {\n        renderedChildren.add(childBlock.id);\n        const childTool = msg.toolSnapshot?.[childBlock.toolCallId];\n        elements.push(\n          childTool !== undefined ? (\n            <ToolCallCard key={childBlock.id} tool={childTool} depth={d} nested />\n          ) : (\n            <Text key={childBlock.id} color={token('textDim', d)}>\n              [tool {childBlock.toolCallId}]\n            </Text>\n          ),\n        );\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <Box flexDirection=\"column\">\n      <Text color={token(roleToken(msg.role), d)} bold>\n        {roleLabel(msg.role)}\n      </Text>\n      {msg.reasoning !== undefined && msg.reasoning.length > 0 ? (\n        <Text color={token('textDim', d)} dimColor>\n          thinking: {msg.reasoning}\n        </Text>\n      ) : null}\n      {elements}\n    </Box>\n  );\n}\n```\n\nWait, I have `renderedChildren` set but never use it meaningfully. Let me remove it. Actually the skip logic handles it — when iterating, child blocks with parent present are skipped. So `renderedChildren` is unnecessary. Let me remove.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the fallback. The brief says: \"a child whose parent block is not present in this message must still render (at top level) — never drop a tool card.\" So if parent block not present, render the child at top level. Should it be nested or not? The brief says \"at top level\" — so not nested. That makes sense.\n\nNow I need to keep `renderBlock` or inline. The brief says \"Keep the existing role label, reasoning line, and text rendering. Only the tool-block grouping changes.\" I'll inline the rendering and can remove `renderBlock` or keep it. Since I'm restructuring, let me remove `renderBlock` and inline. Actually, to minimize changes and keep it clean, let me just rewrite the component body.\n\nHmm, but `renderBlock` is a module-level function. If I don't use it, tsc with strict might complain about unused? No, unused functions are allowed in TS (no `noUnusedLocals` for module-level functions unless enabled). Actually `noUnusedLocals` would flag unused local variables but not unused exported/module functions... actually it does flag unused private functions? Let me just remove `renderBlock` to be safe, or keep it. Actually the brief says keep text rendering. Let me just remove `renderBlock` since I'm inlining everything.\n\nWait, but removing might break other tests that import it? It's not exported. Let me just remove it and inline.\n\nActually, let me keep it simpler — I'll remove `renderBlock` and inline all rendering in the component.\n\nNow for the test file. Let me write comprehensive tests.\n\nLet me look at the harness. I need to build NDJSON lines. Let me write the tests.\n\nFor the reducer test, I need to import `reducer`, `initialState`, and types. Let 