'result', args: {} } as ToolState;\n  const childTool = { name: 'Bash', status: 'result', args: { command: 'wc -l' }, result: '8 lines', parentToolUseId: parentId } as ToolState;\n  \n  const nestedMsg = {\n    id: 'turn-1',\n    role: 'assistant',\n    blocks: [\n      { kind: 'tool', id: 'b1', toolCallId: parentId },\n      { kind: 'tool', id: 'b2', toolCallId: childId },\n    ],\n    toolSnapshot: { [parentId]: parentTool, [childId]: childTool },\n  } as unknown as Msg;\n  \n  const nested = render(createElement(Message, { msg: nestedMsg })).lastFrame();\n  expect(nested).toContain('Agent');\n  expect(nested).toContain('Bash');\n  \n  // Compare against flat (non-nested) render\n  const flatChild = { name: 'Bash', status: 'result', args: { command: 'wc -l' }, result: '8 lines' } as ToolState;\n  const flatMsg = {\n    id: 'turn-1',\n    role: 'assistant',\n    blocks: [\n      { kind: 'tool', id: 'b1', toolCallId: parentId },\n      { kind: 'tool', id: 'b2', toolCallId: childId },\n    ],\n    toolSnapshot: { [parentId]: parentTool, [childId]: flatChild },\n  } as unknown as Msg;\n  \n  const flat = render(createElement(Message, { msg: flatMsg })).lastFrame();\n  expect(nested).not.toEqual(flat);\n});\n```\n\nThis should work. The nested render indents the child card, so the frames differ.\n\nNow let me also think: does `render` from `ink-testing-library` return an object with `lastFrame()` that returns string | undefined? Let me check. `lastFrame()` returns `string | undefined`. So `nested` is `string | undefined`. `expect(nested).toContain('Agent')` — if nested is undefined, this would fail. But it should be a string since we rendered something. Let me add a non-null assertion or check:\n\nActually, `toContain` on undefined would throw. Let me assert defined first:\n```ts\nexpect(nested).toBeDefined();\nexpect(nested!).toContain('Agent');\n```\n\nOr just use `nested!`. Let me be safe.\n\nHmm, actually `lastFrame()` returns `string | undefined`. With `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` OFF, that doesn't change. It's still `string | undefined` because that's the library's type. Let me use `!`.\n\nOK, let me also double check the `makeSpawn` harness. The brief gives:\n```ts\nfunction makeSpawn(lines: string[]): SpawnImpl {\n  return () => ({\n    stdout: (async function* () { for (const l of lines) yield `${l}\\n`; })(),\n    kill: () => true,\n    on(): ChildProcessLike { return this as unknown as ChildProcessLike; },\n  }) as ChildProcessLike;\n}\n```\n\nThis returns a `SpawnImpl` (which is a function). `createClaudeCliClient(cliEntry, { spawnImpl: makeSpawn(lines) })`. Good.\n\nWait, `SpawnImpl` is a function that takes `(command, args, options)` and returns `ChildProcessLike`. The `makeSpawn` returns a function `() => ({...})`. But `SpawnImpl` signature is `(command, args, options) => ChildProcessLike`. The returned function ignores args, which is fine in TS (fewer params is OK). But the return type — `() => ChildProcessLike` vs `(command, args, options) => ChildProcessLike` — a function with fewer params is assignable. So `makeSpawn` returns a `SpawnImpl`-compatible function. But the return type annotation says `SpawnImpl`. Let me check: `return () => ({...}) as ChildProcessLike;` — the function takes no args but `SpawnImpl` expects 3 args. In TS, `() => X` is assignable to `(a, b, c) => X`. So this works. Good.\n\nActually wait, the `on` method: `on(): ChildProcessLike { return this as unknown as ChildProcessLike; }`. The `ChildProcessLike` interface has `on(event: 'exit' | 'close', ...)` and `on(event: 'error', ...)`. The implementation `on(): ChildProcessLike` doesn't match the overloads. But since we cast `as ChildProcessLike`, it bypasses. And in tests, `on` is never called (the adapter calls `child.on('error', ...)` and `child.on('exit', ...)`). Wait, the adapter DOES call `child.on('error', ...)` and `child.on('exit', ...)`. So `on` is called. The implementation returns `this`, which is fine (the return value isn't used). The method signature `on(): ChildProcessLike` — when called as `child.on('error', fn)`, TS checks against `ChildProcessLike.on`'s overloads, not the implementation. Since the object is cast `as ChildProcessLike`, TS sees the correct overloads. At runtime, the implementation runs (ignoring args, returning this). The callback `fn` is never actually called since there's no real error/exit. That's fine for tests. Good.\n\nLet me finalize and write all three files.\n\nOne more check on the adapter: the `emitChildToolCalls` function uses `asObject(block.input)`. The `block.input` — `block` is `JsonObject`, so `block.input` is `unknown`. `asObject` handles it. Good. And `args: asObject(block.input) ?? {}`. Good.\n\nAlso, the helper signature: `function* emitChildToolCalls(message: JsonObject, input: TurnInput, parentToolUseId: string): Generator<AgentEvent>`. Good.\n\nLet me write the files now.\n\nFor Message.tsx, let me make sure I handle the `renderBlock` removal. I'll inline everything. Let me also make sure the keys are stable.\n\nActually, I realize I should keep the code clean. Let me write Message.tsx with the nesting logic inline in the component, and remove the `renderBlock` function.\n\nWait, actually — do any other files import `renderBlock`? It's not exported (no `export`). So it's module-private. Removing it is safe.\n\nLet me write Message.tsx:\n\n```tsx\nimport { Box, Text } from 'ink';\nimport type { ReactElement } from 'react';\nimport type { Block, Msg } from '../core/reducer';\nimport { detectColorDepth, token, type ColorDepth, type FlatTokenName } from './theme';\nimport { ToolCallCard } from './ToolCallCard';\n\nconst DEPTH: ColorDepth = detectColorDepth();\n\nexport interface MessageProps {\n  msg: Msg;\n  depth?: ColorDepth;\n}\n\nfunction roleToken(role: Msg['role']): FlatTokenName {\n  switch (role) {\n    case 'user':\n      return 'roleUser';\n    case 'assistant':\n      return 'roleAssistant';\n    case 'system':\n      return 'roleSystem';\n    case 'tool':\n      return 'textDim';\n  }\n}\n\nfunction roleLabel(role: Msg['role']): string {\n  switch (role) {\n    case 'user':\n      return 'user';\n    case 'assistant':\n      return 'assistant';\n    case 'system':\n      return 'system';\n    case 'tool':\n      return 'tool';\n  }\n}\n\nfunction renderToolCard(msg: Msg, block: Block, d: ColorDepth, nested: boolean): ReactElement {\n  const tool = msg.toolSnapshot?.[block.toolCallId];\n  return tool !== undefined ? (\n    <ToolCallCard key={block.id} tool={tool} depth={d} nested={nested} />\n  ) : (\n    <Text key={block.id} color={token('textDim', d)}>\n      [tool {block.toolCallId}]\n    </Text>\n  );\n}\n\nexport function Message({ msg, depth }: MessageProps): ReactElement {\n  const d = depth ?? DEPTH;\n\n  const parentOf = (toolCallId: string): string | undefined =>\n    msg.toolSnapshot?.[toolCallId]?.parentToolUseId;\n\n  // Build childrenByParent map (committed only — toolSnapshot must be present).\n  const childrenByParent = new Map<string, Block[]>();\n  if (msg.toolSnapshot !== undefined) {\n    for (const block of msg.blocks) {\n      if (block.kind !== 'tool') continue;\n      const pid = parentOf(block.toolCallId);\n      if (pid === undefined) continue;\n      const arr = childrenByParent.get(pid);\n      if (arr === undefined) {\n        childrenByParent.set(pid, [block]);\n      } else {\n        arr.push(block);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  const elements: ReactElement[] = [];\n  for (const block of msg.blocks) {\n    if (block.kind === 'text') {\n      elements.push(\n        <Text key={block.id} color={token(roleToken(msg.role), d)}>\n          {block.text}\n        </Text>,\n      );\n      continue;\n    }\n\n    // tool block\n    const pid = parentOf(block.toolCallId);\n    if (pid !== undefined) {\n      // This is a child. If its parent tool block is also in this message, it\n      // renders under the parent (skip here). Otherwise render at top level\n      // (fallback — never drop a tool card).\n      const parentPresent = msg.blocks.some(\n        (b) => b.kind === 'tool' && b.toolCallId === pid,\n      );\n      if (parentPresent) continue;\n      elements.push(renderToolCard(msg, block, d, false));\n      continue;\n    }\n\n    // Parent or standalone tool block — render it, then its nested children.\n    elements.push(renderToolCard(msg, block, d, false));\n    const children = childrenByParent.get(block.toolCallId);\n    if (children !== undefined) {\n      for (const childBlock of children) {\n        elements.push(renderToolCard(msg, childBlock, d, true));\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <Box flexDirection=\"column\">\n      <Text color={token(roleToken(msg.role), d)} bold>\n        {roleLabel(msg.role)}\n      </Text>\n      {msg.reasoning !== undefined && msg.reasoning.length > 0 ? (\n        <Text color={token('textDim', d)} dimColor>\n          thinking: {msg.reasoning}\n        </Text>\n      ) : null}\n      {elements}\n    </Box>\n  );\n}\n```\n\nWait, there's an issue with `renderToolCard` and the `nested` prop. `ToolCallCardProps` has `nested?: boolean`. Passing `nested={false}` — with `exactOptionalPropertyTypes` OFF, passing `false` to an optional `boolean` prop is fine. But actually, passing `nested={false}` explicitly might differ from not passing it at all. The brief says `nested?: boolean` with \"default off\". So `nested={false}` should be the same as not passing it. Let me check — with `exactOptionalPropertyTypes` OFF, `nested?: boolean` accepts `boolean | undefined`, and passing `false` is fine. The component checks `nested` truthiness, so `false` = off. Good.\n\nBut wait, actually, to be safe and match \"default off\", let me only pass `nested` when it's true:\n\nActually, the `renderToolCard` helper always passes `nested`. For non-nested, `nested={false}`. This should be fine. But let me reconsider — the original code didn't pass `nested` at all (it didn't exist). Now `ToolCallCard` has `nested?: bo